    </ul>
    
    <p class="heading_space"><a name="install" class="heading" id="deadlink">How do I install the plugin?</a></p>
    <ul class="specific">
      <li class="specific">Log into your blog</li>
      <li class="specific">Go to the "Plugins" tab</li>
      <li class="specific">Select the "Add New" option</li>
      <li class="specific">Search for the term "Placeling"</li>
      <li class="specific">Click the link to install and then activate the Placeling plugin</li>
    </ul>
    
    <p class="heading_space"><a name="tag" class="heading" id="deadlink">How I do I tag my post with a location?</a></p>
    <p>After you install the Placeling plugin, you'll notice a new box at the bottom of the compose screen:</p>
    <p>
      <%= image_tag "home/bloggers/new_post.png", :alt=>"Untagged post", :class=>"blog_image" %>
    </p>
      <p>Click "Add Place" and a pop-up window will appear.</p>
      <p>The first time you do this, you'll be asked to log in to Placeling (remember - you must have an account). If you've any issues doing this, <a href="mailto:support@placeling.com" class="specific_link">drop us a line</a>.</p>
      <p>When you're logged in, the pop-up will contain a search box plus any recent locations.</p>
      <p>
        <%= image_tag "home/bloggers/choose_place.png", :alt=>"Recent Places", :class=>"blog_image" %>
      </p>
      <p>If your blog post is about a recent location, simply click the one you want. Otherwise, type the name of the location your blog post is about. As you type, you'll see the list of locations update.</p>
      <p>Tips:
        <ul class="specific">
          <li class="specific">If you're typing a name like "Starbucks" with multiple locations, include a city or street name e.g., "Starbucks Robson"</li>
          <li class="specific">If you don't see any locations that match your term, make sure your spelling is correct</li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>If you don't still don't see the place you're looking for just hit the "enter" or "return" key while typing and you'll be able to add a new place. <a href="#new" class="specific_link">More below</a>.</p>
      <p>Once you see your location, click it and you'll see a footer appear, with a map. If this is the right place, click "Save".</p>
      <p>
        <%= image_tag "home/bloggers/chosen_place.png", :alt=>"Footer Preview", :class=>"blog_image" %>
      </p>
      <p>The name of the location you tagged will appear above the main editor. The Placeling plugin box contains a map of the location plus its name and address.</p>
      <p>Write your blog post and publish it.</p>
      <p>When you publish the following will happen:</p>
      <ul class="specific">
        <li class="specific">The location you selected will be added to your map, if it's not already there</li>
        <li class="specific">The excerpt, tags, photos (optional) and URL to Placeling's servers so that we show the place on the map</li>
      </ul>
      
      <p class="heading_space"><a name="new" class="heading" id="deadlink">How do I add a place that's not in Placeling's database?</a></p>
      <p>If you type in the name of a location and it doesn't appear, just hit the "enter" or "return" key and you'll see an option to add it:</p>
      <p>
        <%= image_tag "home/bloggers/brand_new_place.png", :alt=>"Add New Place Link", :class=>"blog_image" %>
      </p>
      <p>When you click the link, a new tab will open up and send you to Placeling.com (you may need to log in). You'll be asked to fill out the details of the place. You can type an address and the map will update for you (or vice versa):</p>
      <p>
        <%= image_tag "home/bloggers/create_new_place_with_details.png", :alt=>"Create New Place", :class=>"blog_image" %>
      </p>
      <p>You'll then need to confirm the details of the location:</p>
      <p>
        <%= image_tag "home/bloggers/create_new_place_confirm.png", :alt=>"Confirm New Place Details", :class=>"blog_image" %>
      </p>
      <p>After confirming the details, you can close Placeling and go back to your blog. When you click "Add Place" in the Placeling plugin you'll see the new place at the top of the list.</p>
      
      <p class="heading_space"><a name="map" class="heading" id="deadlink">How can I customize the map?</a></p>
      <p>If you open up the page holding your map, you'll see there's a tag called "placeling_map" with two attributes:</p>
      <ul class="specific">
        <li class="specific">
          height - change this to make the map taller/shorter. It will automatically fill the entire width of the page
        </li>
        <li class="specific">
          mobile_auto_scroll - on mobile, this scrolls the page to the top of the map so that the map occupies as much of the page as possible
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>If you open up Placeling's settings, you can change the "home location" - where the map is centered. This will send you over to Placeling.com and you'll need to refresh the page to see the updated location.</p>
      
      <p class="heading_space"><a name="list" class="heading" id="deadlink">How can I see a list of nearby places instead of a map?</a></p>
      <p>You can easily do this, just <%= link_to 'upgrade', blogger_plans_path, :class=>"feature_grid" %> to our premium plugin.</p>
      
      <p class="heading_space"><a name="footer" class="heading" id="deadlink">What is the footer for?</a></p>
      <p>The Placeling plugin puts a little footer at the bottom of each blog post where you tag a location.</p>
      <p>The footer contains a link to your map, so that your readers can explore all the locations you've placemarked.</p>
      <p>The footer only appears in actual posts: it won't appear on the front page of your blog.</p>
      <p>If you ever uninstall the Placeling plugin, the footer will be removed from all posts.</p>
      <p>If you don't want the footer to appear at all, <%= link_to 'upgrade', blogger_plans_path, :class=>"feature_grid" %> to our premium plugin.</p>

